  <!-- SCROLLYTELLING — PINNED NARRATIVE: 5 falls -->
  <section class="pbc-scrolly" id="scrolly" aria-label="The five most common falls">
    <div class="pbc-scrolly-head">
      <h2>Five ways founders fall off.</h2>
      <span class="meta">Scroll to walk through each →</span>
    </div>

    <div class="pbc-scrolly-grid">
      <!-- LEFT: scrolling narrative -->
      <div class="pbc-scrolly-text" id="scrolly-text">
        <div class="pbc-scrolly-step is-active" data-step="0">
          <div>
            <span class="step-num">Fall · 01</span>
            <h3>Secrets in a public repo.</h3>
            <p>You pushed your <code>.env</code> to GitHub. Your OpenAI key, Stripe key, and database password are now scraped within <strong>five minutes</strong>. Bots watch the GitHub event firehose for new keys; the rotation playbook is the only path back.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pbc-scrolly-step" data-step="1">
          <div>
            <span class="step-num">Fall · 02</span>
            <h3>Data loss with no backup.</h3>
            <p>The platform you built on (Replit, Bolt, Lovable) lost or migrated state. There was no export. The work is gone. The first backup you make doesn't count — only the first one you've successfully <em>restored</em> from does.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pbc-scrolly-step" data-step="2">
          <div>
            <span class="step-num">Fall · 03</span>
            <h3>No version control.</h3>
            <p>You can't roll back a bad change because every change overwrote the last one. Git isn't an engineering luxury — it's the only honest record of what you built and why.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pbc-scrolly-step" data-step="3">
          <div>
            <span class="step-num">Fall · 04</span>
            <h3>Deploys that break in prod but not preview.</h3>
            <p>Environment differences you didn't know existed. Different node versions, different env vars, different timezones. The bug isn't in your code — it's in the gap between two machines you treated as identical.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pbc-scrolly-step" data-step="4">
          <div>
            <span class="step-num">Fall · 05</span>
            <h3>A user submits real data and you don't know what applies.</h3>
            <p>GDPR? PII? Payment data? The moment a real human's information lives in your system you're technically liable, whether you knew the rules or not. Compliance is a line you cross, not a feature you ship.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

